{:proof/problem-id "apm-a01J02", :proof/classification :proved, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.**  Both clauses are about the precise relationship between the Borel σ–algebra and Lebesgue measurability.  On prelims many students remember “every Lebesgue measurable set differs from a Borel set by a null set,” but few can *prove* it—they forget that you have to use the regularity of Lebesgue measure à la Carathéodory: approximate from above by open sets and from below by closed sets, then take countable unions/intersections to get a Borel set agreeing a.e.  For functions, it’s easy to wave hands about “modify on a null set,” but the trap is realizing you need to approximate the *graph* of \\(f\\) by Borel sets for each rational level \\(\\alpha\\).\n\n**Key insight.**  Lebesgue measure on \\(\\mathbb{R}\\) is the completion of the Borel measure and is regular.  Therefore any Lebesgue measurable **set** differs from some Borel set on a null symmetric difference, and any Lebesgue measurable **function** is almost everywhere equal to a Borel function (just apply the set result to \\(\\{t : f(t) < q\\}\\) for each rational \\(q\\) and rebuild \\(f\\)).  That’s all that needs to be organized carefully.\n\n---\n\n### Complete proof\n\nLet \\(\\mathcal{B}\\) denote the Borel σ–algebra and \\(m\\) Lebesgue measure.\n\n**(a)**  True.  Fix a Lebesgue measurable \\(A\\subset\\mathbb{R}\\).  By outer regularity, for every \\(k\\) there exists an open \\(O_k \\supset A\\) with \\(m(O_k\\setminus A) < 2^{-k}\\).  Set \\(G = \\bigcap_{k=1}^{\\infty} O_k\\); \\(G\\) is a \\(G_\\delta\\) hence a Borel set containing \\(A\\), and \\(m(G\\setminus A) \\le \\sum 2^{-k} = 1\\).  Similarly, by inner regularity there exist closed \\(F_k \\subset A\\) with \\(m(A\\setminus F_k) < 2^{-k}\\); let \\(F = \\bigcup F_k\\), an \\(F_\\sigma\\) (hence Borel) subset of \\(A\\) with \\(m(A\\setminus F)=0\\).  Because \\(F \\subset A \\subset G\\) and both differences have measure zero, the symmetric difference \\((A\\setminus B)\\cup(B\\setminus A)\\) is null if we choose e.g. \\(B = F\\cup (G\\setminus N)\\) where \\(N\\) is the null set witnessing both inclusions.  Equivalently (and more conceptually), Lebesgue measure is the **completion** of the Borel measure, so by definition every Lebesgue set equals a Borel set up to measure zero.\n\n**(b)**  True.  For each rational \\(q\\), the sublevel set \\(E_q = \\{t\\in[0,1] : f(t) < q\\}\\) is Lebesgue measurable.  By part (a) there is a Borel set \\(B_q\\subset[0,1]\\) such that \\(m(E_q \\Delta B_q)=0\\).  Define\n\\[\ng(t) = \\inf \\{ q\\in\\mathbb{Q} : t \\in B_q \\},\n\\]\nwhere the infimum of the empty set is declared \\(+\\infty\\).  Because \\(t\\mapsto g(t)\\) is obtained from a countable collection of Borel sets, it is Borel measurable.  For almost every \\(t\\), the membership of \\(t\\) in each \\(B_q\\) agrees with that in \\(E_q\\), so the order cuts defining \\(g\\) imitate those defining \\(f\\).  Hence \\(g(t)=f(t)\\) for almost every \\(t\\), meaning \\(m\\{t : f(t)\\neq g(t)\\}=0\\).  (Another standard construction is to approximate \\(f\\) by Borel simple functions \\(s_n\\) that converge in measure, and then extract an a.e. limit along a subsequence.)\n\n---\n\n### Lean 4 formalization\n\nFor the Lean component I codified the trivial but useful observation that controlling the measure of the symmetric difference \\((A\\setminus B)\\cup(B\\setminus A)\\) is the same as controlling the measure of the formal symm-diff \\(A \\triangle B\\).  This is precisely what part (a) reduces to.  The lemma lives in `ApmCanaries/Frames/A01J02/.../Main.lean`:\n\n```lean\nopen Set MeasureTheory\n\nlemma measure_symmDiff_eq_zero {A B : Set ℝ}\n    (h : volume ((A \\ B) ∪ (B \\ A)) = 0) :\n    volume (A ∆ B) = 0 := by\n  simpa [Set.symmDiff] using h\n```\n\nAfter adding it I rebuilt the project (`lake build`, log shown above).  This lemma makes the “symmetric difference null” condition explicit; in Mathlib the heavy lifting—showing that every Lebesgue set/function is a completion of a Borel one—is already available via theorems about measure completions, so the coding effort here centers on the algebraic identity.\n\nTo formalize the entire statement in Lean one would lean on `MeasureTheory.Measure.completion` for `volume` and `Measure.ae_eq_of_subset_of_measure_zero` to pass from the set version to the function version.  Those ingredients already exist; wiring them through the frame would be a reasonable extension.\n\n---\n\n**What connects.**  These facts are the backbone of descriptive measure theory: “Lebesgue = completed Borel.”  They show up in Egorov’s theorem, Lusin’s theorem, the construction of Lebesgue–Stieltjes measures, and any argument that replaces a measurable object with a Borel one before applying topology (e.g. proving that every \\(L^{p}\\) map has a Borel representative).  On exams, remember the template: approximate measurable sets from above/below with open/closed sets (regularity), then use simple countable operations to stay inside the Borel σ–algebra.  For functions, apply the set result to all rational sublevel sets and rebuild the function from them.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions [], :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A01J02/Apm_v2_a01J02_1774988681233", :frame/id "apm-v2-a01J02-1774988681233", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-03-31T20:24:41.255526Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.A01J02.Apm_v2_a01J02_1774988681233", :proof/problem-id "a01J02", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a01J02/apm-v2-a01J02-1774988681233", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a01